df_production_daily = df.groupby('date', as_index=False).agg({
    'capacity': 'sum',
    'volume': 'sum',
    'percentage': 'mean',
    'emission': 'sum',
    'emissionfactor': 'mean'
})

By looking at this graph we can see that in general the energy production is higher in the summer months. However this graph is not very useful for details, as there are too many data points in it. However, we can see the production of solar energy has increased over the years.

That's why we will look at the volume per month, and make a new graph so we can get a better overview.

In [64]:
from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter

df_production_daily['Year'] = df_production_daily['date'].dt.year
df_production_daily['Month'] = df_production_daily['date'].dt.month

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.lineplot(x=df_production_daily['Month'], y=df_production_daily['volume'], hue=df_production_daily['Year'], palette='pastel')

plt.title('Total Volume per Month', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Month', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Total Volume (kWh)', fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(ticks=range(1, 13), labels=['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'], rotation=45)
plt.legend(title='Year', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.grid(True)

formatter = FuncFormatter(lambda x, _: f'{x:,.0f}')
plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Here we can clearly see the total energy production is higher in the summer months compared to the winter. This seems logical, however we will still compare the data to weather data to see the total amount of sun hours. We can also see there are some fluctuations in the data and that it is not a smooth line. This is because the data is aggregated from hourly data to daily data, and it is most likely influenced by the weather and the total amount of sun hours.

What is also interesting to see is that the total energy production appears to be overall higher in 2023, this could be because the amount of solar panels in the Netherlands has grown. We will look at this at a later point.

In [65]:
df_season = df.copy()
df_season['Month'] = df['date'].dt.month
df_season['Year'] = df['date'].dt.year

monthly_data = df_season.groupby(['Year', 'Month'])['volume'].sum().reset_index()

season_map = {12: 'Winter', 1: 'Winter', 2: 'Winter', 
              3: 'Spring', 4: 'Spring', 5: 'Spring', 
              6: 'Summer', 7: 'Summer', 8: 'Summer', 
              9: 'Autumn', 10: 'Autumn', 11: 'Autumn'}

season_order = ['Winter', 'Spring', 'Summer', 'Autumn']

df_season['Season'] = df_season['Month'].map(season_map)

seasonal_data = df_season.groupby(['Year', 'Season'])['volume'].sum().reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x='Season', y='volume', hue='Year', data=seasonal_data, palette='pastel', order=season_order)
plt.title('Total Solar Energy Generation by Season')
plt.ylabel('Energy Generated (in kWh)')

plt.gca().yaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)

plt.show()

This bar chart confirms that the solar energy production is higher in the summer months. What is interesting is that the difference between the years in the winter is not that big compared to the summer.

In this notebook we will only look at the solar energy production, for this reason we will also only look at the weather data that is related to the solar energy production. Sunshine and the amount of sun hours are not the only factor. The temperature can be important, the cloud coverage is important and even wind could impact the solar energy production (source). We will drop the other columns for that reason.

for ax in axes:
    handles, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    labels = [str(round(float(label))) for label in labels]
    ax.legend(handles, labels, title="Year")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

These bar charts are not very surprising, they show that the temperature and average sunshine per hour are higher in summer compared to the colder months. What is interesting is that the average sunshine per hour and the average global radiation were both higher in 2022, compared to the other years. We can see the average sunshine per hour and average global radiation in the winter are both very close to each other, being slightly higher in 2021. This could explain why the difference in solar energy production in the winter months is not that big.

Correlation between solar production and weather¶

Next we will look at the correlation between the weather and the total energy production. For this we will combine both datasets.

In [94]:
growth_installations_2021_2022 = ((2298859 - 1730285) / 1730285) * 100
growth_installations_2022_2023 = ((2875487 - 2298859) / 2298859) * 100

growth_production_2021_2022 = ((18386170134 - 12296723156) / 12296723156) * 100
growth_production_2022_2023 = ((21796804777 - 18386170134) / 18386170134) * 100

print(f"Installations growth 2021 to 2022: {growth_installations_2021_2022:.2f}%")
print(f"Installations growth 2022 to 2023: {growth_installations_2022_2023:.2f}%\n")
print(f"Energy production growth 2021 to 2022: {growth_production_2021_2022:.2f}%")
print(f"Energy production growth 2022 to 2023: {growth_production_2022_2023:.2f}%")

Installations growth 2021 to 2022: 32.86%
Installations growth 2022 to 2023: 25.08%

Energy production growth 2021 to 2022: 49.52%
Energy production growth 2022 to 2023: 18.55%

By looking at the growth in both the amount of solar panels and the solar energy production we can see there has been a significant growth in solar panels between 2022 and 2021. The total amount still increased in 2023, but the growth has slowed down a bit. The growth in solar energy production has increased significantly between 2022 and 2021. This could have different reasons, one of them being the amount of solar panels or even improvements to make the solar panels more efficient in producing energy. The growth in production between 2023 and 2022 has slowed down a lot compared to the previous year. In the graph we saw earlier it we found out that the amount of sunshine per hour and average global radiation was higher in 2022 compared to 2023. This could be one of the reasons why the growth in energy production was lower compared to the previous year.

There is a really big correlation between the amount of solar panels in the Netherlands and the total solar energy production. This is not very surprising, since the solar energy is produced using the solar panels.

Conclusion¶

There are multiple factors that influence the total solar energy production. The biggest factor seems to be the amount of solar panels, which is obvious. Sadly this data is only available per year, so we cannot really use it for making our model. We also found out the weather does have an influence on the solar energy production, so we will use the weather data that is available to make a model.
